@section Scope and Purpose

This document describes a new implementation of CMU Common Lisp (nee
Spice Lisp) as it is implemented on the DinkyMachine @footnote{Note
that the DinkyMachine is essentially what would become the CMU CL and
later SBCL virtual machine. The name is used here to distinguish the
RT PC backend format from PERQ and Vax at a moment of transitioning
all development to the new backend.} running Mach, a Berkeley Unix 4.3
binary compatible operating system. This design is undergoing rapid
change, and for the present is not guaranteed to accurately describe
any past, present, or future implementation of CMU Common Lisp. All
questions and comments on this material should be directed to David
B. McDonald (David.McDonald@@CS.CMU.EDU).
@cindex DinkyMachine

This document specifies the hand-coded assembler routines (miscops) and
virtual memory architecture of the DinkyMachine CMU Common Lisp system.
This is a working document, and it will change frequently as the system is
developed and maintained. If some detail of the system does not agree with
what is specified here, it is to be considered a bug.

@section Notational Conventions
@cindex Bit numbering
@cindex Byte numbering
CMU Common Lisp objects are 32 bits long. The high-order bit of each word is
numbered 0; the low-order bit is numbered 31. If a word is broken into smaller
units, these are packed into the word from left to right. For example, if we
break a word into bytes, byte 0 would occupy bits 0-7, byte 1 would occupy
8-15, byte 2 would occupy 16-23, and byte 3 would occupy 24-31.

All CMU Common Lisp documentation uses decimal as the default radix; other
radices will be indicated by a subscript (as in 77@-[8]) or by a clear
statement of what radix is in use.

@node Data Types and Object Formats
@chapter Data Types and Object Formats

@node Lisp Objects
@section Lisp Objects
@cindex lisp object

lisp objects are 32 bits long. They come in 32 basic types, divided
into three classes: immediate data types, pointer types, and
forwarding pointer types. The storage formats are as follows:

@cindex immediate object format
@cindex pointer object format


@smallexample
Immediate Data Types:
 0             4 5                                                   31
------------------------------------------------------------------------
| Type Code (5) |              Immediate Data (27)                     |
------------------------------------------------------------------------

Pointer and Forwarding Types:
 0             4 5              6 7                     29           31
------------------------------------------------------------------------
| Type Code (5) | Space Code (2) |    Pointer (23)        | Unused (2) |
------------------------------------------------------------------------
@end smallexample



